<subSubSection id="24CEE52604EDD060A18EE08E7BF0623F" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="description">
<paragraph id="FC66EDCEE4D17C5C2C66C70B6B0AAC5C" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0176E105DF56AA0CC5B059E59E5A9844" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Herbs, shrubs, trees, or vines, with or without prickles, glabrous or pubescent with unbranched or branched (including stellate), often glandular hairs. Leaves alternate or paired and frequently unequal in size, simple to pinnately lobed or compound, petiolate or sessile, without stipules, but sometimes with 
<normalizedToken id="2ED6A80EB65607F3CEF19D8AAF88AF26" originalValue="“pseudostipules”">&quot;pseudostipules&quot;</normalizedToken>
(Potato clade). Inflorescences cymose, branched or unbranched. Flowers usually perfect, (4-) 5-merous, actinomorphic or zygomorphic; calyx campanulate, sometimes accrescent in fruit, corolla rotate, campanulate, stellate, or urceolate, white, green, yellow, pink, or purple; stamens equal or unequal, the filaments generally short and inserted at the corolla base, the anthers basifixed, equal or unequal, blunt or tapered toward apex, opening by terminal pores, these sometimes expanding into longitudinal slits, or introrsely longitudinally dehiscent with age in sect. 
<taxonomicName id="2C44A888EB1E18B85CC3189CCDE5702C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Lycopersicon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="609F06B2612271B2F412824CB0570FBA" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Lycopersicon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; ovary 2-carpellate; ovules many; style articulated at base or above the base, usually slender; stigma capitate to elongate-clavate. Fruit a berry, usually fleshy but occasionally dry, usually many-seeded, the seeds often flattened; embryo curved, embedded in abundant endosperm. Chromosome number: n = 12, 23, 24, 48.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D4E41344B1DE903A71E9DE0A8E4C65A3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="76CE4CB82ECFD71FB9BBE84250435C21" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA218DCC0659CEC4F88934B33175AE19" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
The generic description applies to 
<taxonomicName id="FE4132B9201494AFDD92148718B89E83" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Solanales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6E41A6AD0C8D1AACF7E564634020140F" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Solanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including all those genera traditionally segregated from it: 
<taxonomicName id="036064F88A812B9D167FF2E1096E07DF" authorityName="C.F.P.Martius ex Sendtner" authorityYear="1845" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Cyphomandra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D7EDE8EF0964B8A90504E332BBA0B0B1" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Cyphomandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Bohs 1995), 
<taxonomicName id="BB028FFA906E47FC05CA8479775F6D0C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Lycopersicon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B5637BFF51C32BC0A731AAB0FE4BD829" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Lycopersicon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B9065B1A8C1736C8F779F53F075D8930" author="Spooner, DM" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="324" pageNumber="325" pagination="676 - 688" refId="B147" refString="Spooner, DM, Anderson, GJ, Jansen, RK, 1993. Chloroplast DNA evidence for the interrealtionships of tomatoes, potatoes, and pepinos (Solanaceae). American Journal of Botany 80: 676 - 688" title="Chloroplast DNA evidence for the interrealtionships of tomatoes, potatoes, and pepinos (Solanaceae)." volume="80" year="1993">Spooner et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="2E4E5C74A0150565114CDF8C21A0F61C" author="Peralta, IE" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany Monographs" pageId="323" pageNumber="324" pagination="1 - 186" refId="B130" refString="Peralta, IE, Spooner, DM, Knapp, S, 2008. Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae). Systematic Botany Monographs 84: 1 - 186" title="Taxonomy of wild tomatoes and their relatives (Solanum sections Lycopersicoides, Juglandifolia, Lycopersicon; Solanaceae)." volume="84" year="2008">Peralta et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="6C51CCCA0EC9F3C8DAEACD0DE5562DC8" class="Ostracoda" family="Not" genus="Normania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Not" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="542E6632CA8C21F00A4A8AB1AD7051DB" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Normania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="D73E96386D531274347FEDB4075E35F1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Triguera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Solanales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C7C85E15ACF2CF38BE98F2C9409BFEF4" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Triguera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E07C7FCD03C32343ECCC86261BDF10E4" author="Bohs, L" journalOrPublisher="Pland Systematics and Evolution" pageId="317" pageNumber="318" pagination="33 - 48" publicationUrl="10.1007/s006060170035" refId="B17" refString="Bohs, L, Olmstead, RG, 2001. A reassessment of Normania and Triguera (Solanaceae). Pland Systematics and Evolution 228: 33 - 48, 10.1007/s006060170035" title="A reassessment of Normania and Triguera (Solanaceae)." url="10.1007/s006060170035" volume="228" year="2001">Bohs and Olmstead 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Data from chloroplast DNA sequences strongly support the inclusion of these segregates in a monophyletic 
<taxonomicName id="4753F433854D7F736E7AE2B5C7108331" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Solanales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="89B64BA8DDE5D5F2280D981275D76033" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Solanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="DD162F3E1CBD95ADAD34948EC2915791" author="Bohs, L" editor="Keating, RC" journalOrPublisher="D'Arcy: the legacy of a taxonomist, Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden, Vol. 104. Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis" pageId="317" pageNumber="318" pagination="27 - 49" refId="B16" refString="Bohs, L, 2005. Major clades in Solanum based on ndh F sequences. In: Keating, RC, Hollowell, VC, Croat, TB, Eds., A festschrift for William G. D'Arcy: the legacy of a taxonomist, Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden, Vol. 104. Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis: 27 - 49" title="Major clades in Solanum based on ndh F sequences." volumeTitle="A festschrift for William G." year="2005">Bohs 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Some workers (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="8FEC88B4660A4A69B7D788838A0CB396" author="Hunziker, AT" journalOrPublisher="Lorentzia" pageId="319" pageNumber="320" refId="B64" refString="Hunziker, AT, 2001. Genera Solanacearum, the genera of Solanaceae illustrated, arranged according to a new system. ARG Gantner Verlag, Ruggell, Liechtenstein,." title="Genera Solanacearum, the genera of Solanaceae illustrated, arranged according to a new system. ARG Gantner Verlag, Ruggell, Liechtenstein," year="2001">Hunziker 2001</bibRefCitation>
) maintain these taxa as distinct genera.
</paragraph>
